subject: cmsdk: add CMSettings option for toggling mobile data with one tap [2/3]

values.-1: Fails
values.+1: Verified

values.-1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this
values.+1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

messages.message: Uploaded patch set 1.
Uploaded patch set 2: Commit message was updated.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

This patch produces a build error:

out/target/common/obj/PACKAGING/cm_public_api.txt:1225: error 5: Added public field cyanogenmod.providers.CMSettings.System.QS_ENABLE_MOBILE_DATA_ONETAP_TOGGLE

******************************
You have tried to change the API from what has been previously approved.

STOP.
  Read this:
  https://github.com/LineageOS/cm_platform_sdk/wiki/Creating-an-API-for-the-SDK#updating--verifying-the-api

Patch Set 2: Verified-1 Code-Review-2

Won't merge. An option for this "feature" is pointless

Patch Set 2:

> Won't merge. An option for this "feature" is pointless

Why not?

Patch Set 2:

This is not cm7 where the more toggles you have the better it is. In a real world scenario no one is going to switch a such thing an and off often so it'd just be another "look how cool it is: my rom has more toggles than yours. I can toggle anything feature on and off because it's just cool seeing the entry in the settings list".

Also me (and others) are not fans of changing the aosp behavior, so I'm not even sure if the fw-side change will be ever merged

Patch Set 2:

> This is not cm7 where the more toggles you have the better it is.
 > In a real world scenario no one is going to switch a such thing an
 > and off often so it'd just be another "look how cool it is: my rom
 > has more toggles than yours. I can toggle anything feature on and
 > off because it's just cool seeing the entry in the settings list".
 > 
 > Also me (and others) are not fans of changing the aosp behavior, so
 > I'm not even sure if the fw-side change will be ever merged

It's not a question of being better because there are more toggles. Like Dan said, people would accidentally toggle mobile data, that's why I added a setting to enable this feature, which is disabled by default. It's not useless and it would be useful for many users: you don't have to expand the data tile to enable it, you can just one tap and toggle it.

And regarding changing the AOSP behavior, well, if you're not fans of changing it, then why does Lineage have all the features it has today? I'm pretty sure most of them change the AOSP behavior and you're perfectly fine with it.

I know it's your opinion about it, but now I'm telling you mine, and it's not a reasonable argument to use to reject something that you think is going to be useless.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

This feature would be nice. I have turning data on/off when I need check some things on the internet, and tapping twice to turning it on is quite not user friendly. I have better battery life when is turned off then turned on whole time between charging.

messages.message: Uploaded patch set 1.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

If the device adds an overlay that says "enable by default" then this trumps that and turns it off anyway.  Sounds wrong to me.

Patch Set 1:

A device which only has GPU transform available for LiveDisplay should not be allowed to "enable by default" anyways.
So in any case this patch will prevent ill behaviour due to misconfiguration.

Patch Set 1:

If you think that a device shouldn't be allowed to control the overlay then you should remove it.

Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Patch Set 1:

As discussed internally, a follow up commit will change the behavior:
If your device is only capable of doing GPU transform but you still choose to enforce the overlay, this will be honored (and a warning will be written to logcat).
Uploaded patch set 2.
Abandoned

Patch Set 2:

Why was this abandoned?

Patch Set 2:

Because no one seemed to care/ everyone was opposed.
I can restore if wanted though.

Patch Set 2:

LiveDisplay is enabled by default now (since last year) globally, which means devices that only have GPU transform are "broken". Instead of making those devices overlay the default to false, we should restore this patch IMO to automatically do it.
Restored

Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I have previously verified that this works, but, I am still midly (but only midly) bothered by the fact that it overrides the device overlay.

That is, if the device does not have gpu support then the overlay is completely ignored.  Whether it is unset, set to true or set to false is irrelevant.

As I said before, having a warning to let a maintainer know why changing the overlay didn't work would make that much more user friendly for people doing stupid things.

Patch Set 2:

I thought the plan discussed a long time ago was to completely disable livedisplay if not supported in hardware ?  Playback of protected content breaks with gpu based livedisplay and the end user doesn't know why.
